How to fix pod-level autoscaling not happening, what will be your approach .

When pod autoscaling doesn’t work, I first check HPA status and events, then verify metrics availability and resource requests. 
Most issues come from missing metrics-server or missing CPU requests. I validate HPA targets, workload compatibility, cluster capacity, 
and autoscaler behavior. 
Finally, I simulate load to confirm scaling and add monitoring to prevent recurrence.”

HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler) is a Kubernetes feature that automatically scales the number of pod replicas 
for a workload based on observed metrics, 
ensuring performance while optimizing cost.

HPA:
Increases pods when load is high
Decreases pods when load is low
Works automatically without manual intervention

suppose we have application configured with hpa where it was running fine but suddenly it is not running what will be your approach?

Ans. Check HPA status:
kubectl get hpa <hpa-name>
kubectl describe hpa <hpa-name>

Verify metrics Availability

“I first check HPA status, events, and metrics availability. I verify pod resource requests, 
HPA target configuration, and cluster capacity. I inspect controller and Metrics Server logs, 
simulate load to validate scaling, and apply corrective actions such as fixing metrics, requests, or scaling node pools. Finally, 
I monitor the system to prevent recurrence.”

How to access application if Ingress is configured but not accessible to end users, how you will resolve ?

Ans.
INGRESS:
An Ingress is a Kubernetes resource that defines rules for routing external HTTP/HTTPS traffic to services inside the cluster.

What is an Ingress Controller?
An Ingress Controller is a pod/service running in the cluster.

Popular Ingress Controllers:
NGINX Ingress Controller
Traefik
HAProxy Ingress
AWS ALB Ingress Controller
Istio Gateway (service mesh ingress)

